Publication of the National Emphysema Treatment Trial (NETT) in 2003 established 
lung volume reduction surgery (LVRS) as a viable treatment of select patients 
with moderate to severe emphysema, and the only intervention since the 
availability of ambulatory supplemental oxygen to improve survival. Despite 
these findings, surgical treatment has been underused in part because of concern 
for high morbidity and mortality. This article reviews recent literature 
generated since the original NETT publication, focusing on physiologic 
implications of LVRS, recent data regarding the safety and durability of LVRS, 
and patient selection and extension of NETT criteria to other patient 
populations.

